WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:17.000
This is Emily Crosby with Timothy Jenkins on December 9th, 2015 at the Library of Congress.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:23.000
And we're here as part of the Civil Rights History Project, which is co-sponsored by the Library of Congress

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:28.000
and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:32.000
And also here are John Bishop and I'm Crosby Shanker.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:35.000
Good morning, Tim. Thanks for joining us.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:36.000
Sure.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:41.000
Can you start by telling us when and where you were born and about your family?

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:48.000
I was born in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, December 30th, 1938.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:51.000
Can you tell us about your family?

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:59.000
My mother and father were long-term Philadelphia.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:03.000
My father originated from Richmond, Virginia.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:09.000
And my mother had been born in Philadelphia.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:20.000
And my mother was a housewife and just volunteer in many different church activities.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:28.000
And my father had a barber shop in Philadelphia that was quite an unusual shop

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:34.000
because of its mixed clientele of professionals and lay people.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:41.000
And they gave me quite an exposure to all strata of life in Philadelphia.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:44.000
My grandparents are of some interest.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:51.000
On my mother's side, he was a...weam Albert.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:54.000
He was...weam Albert Jones.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:02:04.000
He was a member of the school board and active Republican promoter after reconstruction

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:08.000
and formed an organization in Philadelphia,

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:12.000
called Remember John Brown.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:19.000
My paternal grandfather was also interested in education.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:29.000
He founded one of the Rosenwald schools in Portland, Virginia,

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:37.000
called the Courtland, Virginia, Normal and Industrial and Normal in the United States.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:46.000
He was part of the following wave after Booker T. Washington's creation of Tuskegee Institute.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:51.000
It's now a historic site in Portland, Virginia.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:56.000
Courtland, Virginia used to be New Jerusalem.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:02.000
It was renamed after the Nat Turner Rebellion.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:11.000
So, what was the Remember John Brown? What was that organization about?

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:17.000
Well, it was basically an organization for black Republicans.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:22.000
It met on a regular basis, at least annually, and sometimes more frequently.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:29.000
And they dealt with questions of finding financial support for blacks

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:33.000
and developing businesses and educational institutions,

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:42.000
and also for other aspects of civil concern dealing with public issues of Philadelphia.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:52.000
And so, did what you mentioned that both of your grandfathers were active in Republican party?

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:54.000
Or both of them actually?

00:03:54.000 --> 00:04:00.000
No, I don't know about my paternal grandfather, but given the time,

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:10.000
and given the fact that he was a Rosenwald institution and what Virginia was like after reconstruction,

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:16.000
I wouldn't be surprised if he too were Republican.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:21.000
So, was he, you said he founded? Was he then the principal of the...

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:27.000
Well, actually, I have a wonderful picture of him sitting in his wicker chair

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:35.000
with his faculty around him and his students behind him in front of this clabbard wood building.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:49.000
And it has Reverend OG Jenkins, president of the Courtland Normalant and Industrial Institute.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:57.000
Sounds like that you had a very strong background with both of your sets of grandparents

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:02.000
in terms of land, education, and politics.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:08.000
Were you, did that influence you growing up? Was that something you were thinking about or where?

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:16.000
Well, I didn't, it wasn't until later that I discovered my paternal grandfather's history and contributions

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:26.000
and started reading some of the old newspaper articles that my aunt had of her father's work when he was in Richmond.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:37.000
He founded what is still the largest African-American Zion Episcopal Church in Richmond called Hood Temple.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:50.000
I have visited there with my children and I've also became aware of his activities in development of different programs in Northern Virginia.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:58.000
But I didn't know that when I was a youngster, I really researched that as an adult.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:04.000
So, what was your childhood like in Philadelphia? What was your own schooling like?

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:15.000
I had something of a peculiar educational career. I did not go to the neighborhood school.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:24.000
I went to a special school of practice. It was called the Thaddeus Stevens School of Practice.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:31.000
It was a training facility for teachers and the production of teachers.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:43.000
It had a student body that was drawn from all over the city and more concentrated in the neighborhood adjacent to the school.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:07:00.000
It was at Spring Garden Street in Philadelphia and it's still there, although I think it's sold to a developer and going to become either offices or condominiums.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:03.000
So, was that an integrated school?

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:17.000
Oh, heavily integrated. In fact, there were a few African-American students. There were Chinese students. There were European immigrants who were there.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:29.000
And they had a broad concentration of Jewish, Irish and Eastern European background students.

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:41.000
It was an interesting environment because we had a very extensive field program.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:51.000
The teachers used to load us up on buses and take us down to the museums. The Art Museum of Philadelphia was quite famous.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:08:05.000
The Fills Institute, Planetarium, Natural History Museum. Some of that had lasting impacts on me.

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:16.000
I fell in love with a grammar school student with the Eastern Asian aesthetic traditions.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:23.000
I was fascinated by a room that they had the Philadelphia Art Museum called the Scholars Room.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:31.000
And to this day, I have a reminiscence of that room and I've tried to duplicate some of it in my own study.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:39.000
Sounds like an interesting start. What made you decide to go to Howard University for college?

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:52.000
Well, I was recruited by a parapetetic promoter who set up appointments in Philadelphia in the school that I went to.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:58.000
Central High was kind of the premier public institution in Philadelphia.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:08.000
And so they always made it a part of their schedule to stop at Central High and give out literature on Howard.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:13.000
And the solicit students who might apply for scholarships.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:24.000
And I made that application and was successful and got a full tuition scholarship to go to Howard.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:31.000
And it made sort of a selection for me. But I also had some family knowledge about Howard.

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:37.000
I had a sister who had gone to West Virginia state and she knew about Howard.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:41.000
I had a brother who had gone to Lincoln University and he knew about Howard.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:48.000
Another sister who had gone to Cheney University all historically black colleges.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:56.000
And Howard also had a connection with one of my neighborhood friends.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:03.000
One of my father's clients ran a confectionery store.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:11.000
And his sister was the dean of women at Howard and he told me lots of the background of Howard and all of it.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:16.000
Sounded interesting and especially interesting to get out of Philadelphia.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:26.000
Most of my time had been in Philadelphia and I wanted to see a new environment and Washington sounded very attractive.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:30.000
When did you enter Howard?

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:38.000
Immediately after completion of high school that would have been 1956.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:42.000
And what was Howard like in those years?

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:50.000
Howard really had a character that was very stimulating.

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:57.000
It had a very vibrant program of student activities.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:02.000
I quickly got involved in the debate society.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:11.000
I got involved in the classics group and we had a philosophy club that was engaging.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:33.000
But most importantly we had a very rich collection of faculty members who by their background had been involved in a lot of the social action interest of the black community for decades.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:44.000
Rayford Logan who was one of my professors in history is of course famous for his black reconstruction studies.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:56.000
He also was the general secretary for the Pan-African movement which W.E. Du Bois was chairman.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:26.000
Then I had Sterling Brown, poet, rock on tour and linguistic critic who introduced us to the whole business of dialect as a form of communication and the history of black literary contributions from the beginning of the American revolution with Philist

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:32.000
who was quickly down to the current poets and writers of the day.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:37.000
And Sterling Brown was more than just the teacher.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:44.000
We came to in dear him as a colleague.

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:58.000
He gave us to his home frequently and there with people like Stokeley Carmichael and Cortland Cox and Jean Wheeler.

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:09.000
We were able to absorb both the music that he provided. He had lots of blues and jazz and how history of that sort of thing.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:21.000
So he created an entree between the academy and the people of the field and the folk traditions of the South.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:30.000
Before coming to Howard he had been at Virginia Union and he had been to some other historically black colleges and he had a rich background.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:48.000
And his father who was also named Sterling Nelson Brown and his father was a biblical scholar and may have started the first correspondence school for black ministers.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:58.000
His observation had been that whereas many people had gone into the ministry in the South they didn't go through seminaries, they didn't go through college.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:07.000
And they had the barest understanding of really the scientific theology.

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:14.000
So he started to develop a program that would correspond with these ministers.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:22.000
And they would have regular reading assignments and they would have exams and they would have questionnaires that they had in the fill out.

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:37.000
And to my knowledge he started this in the early 1900s. It was the first evidence I can find of a correspondence course through the mail to qualify people to be seminarians.

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:54.000
But in addition to those two we had Harold Lewis who was a political scientist and deeply involved in many of the social movements from labor movements on through modern movements.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:15:14.000
And he was a rich source for us. And I could go on and on about the various faculty members of course E. Franklin Frazier was my professor in sociology and his famous study of the black bourgeoisie.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:26.000
And these teachers offered a special access through a vehicle which was called the Little Forum.

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:37.000
And that was an informal reading club that assembled once a month in one of the lobbies of one of the residential halls, Cook Hall.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:49.000
And it allowed a student and a faculty member to present a praises and interpretations of one book per session.

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:56.000
And both a faculty member and a student would comment and then be open for discussion and we'd have cookies and coffee afterwards.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:16:06.000
It's interesting to me that the low these many years when I hear some of my colleagues on radio and TV interviews talk about their background.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:13.000
They lift up this little form as one of the pillars of their educational preparation.

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:23.000
It was particularly important because it was the only form that we had where students and faculty were on a peer relationship.

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:35.000
And the opinions of students were weighted as heavily as those of faculty. We were free to criticize and object and protest what some of the faculty members were saying.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:47.000
And it became a melting pot for thinking about both the mixture of our formal studies and the current events of the time.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:52.000
So the little form is one of the most important features of Howard.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:17:00.000
I got involved in student politics and ultimately ran for student council and became president of student body.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:10.000
And that exposed me to, of course, the politics of the university and also the politics of the students and the fraternities and all that sort of thing.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:19.000
And most importantly, it gave me access to the president of the university, both formally and informally.

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:26.000
He was the doctor Morterkai Wyatt Johnson, the first black president of Howard University.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:31.000
And he was an enormously important person in the whole world of scholarship.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:37.000
He was important because of who he was but also the kind of issues that he spoke to.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:40.000
He was president of Howard during the McCarthy era.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:55.000
And he refused to dismiss any of the people at the House on American Activities Committee, the Senate Committee under McCarthy, tried to expose or excoriate for being left the sympathizers.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:18:03.000
And throughout all that, he continued with a heavy subsidy of money coming from the federal government.

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:10.000
He resisted the pressures to modify or expel the students.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:30.000
Significantly, one of the students, Pauline Murray, set in at the cafeteria in the House of Representatives in the 1940s.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:50.000
And the Capitol Police arrested them and they tried to get them expelled Morterkai Johnson would not expel them as he wouldn't expel any of the faculty who were pursued by congressional types.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:19:16.000
With your politics at the involvement in politics at Howard, did you ever talk to you about the negotiations or how he walked this line between the congressional support funding and what's going on on campus or did you observe that?

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:22.000
I'm afraid we didn't have exactly a peer relationship.

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:26.000
I stole little bits and pieces of his time.

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:32.000
He used to have a house that was on campus.

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:39.000
And he would walk from his house to his office, which is also, of course, on campus.

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:48.000
And I used to wailay him on the path that he would use because his secretary would never give me an appointment.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:57.000
And he used to sit down with me on the long granite bench behind, found his library, and have these wonderful conversations about this and that.

00:19:57.000 --> 00:20:07.000
But mostly it was concerning the University of Publicity and things that we were upset about and things that we were demanding in terms of curriculum of faculty changes.

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:18.000
And that was our kind of informal learning bench, on the granite walk behind Founders Library.

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:24.000
So you mentioned the various things that the students were interested in or protesting.

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:31.000
So you're senior year at Howard must have coincided with the start of the sitting movement.

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:36.000
What kinds of things were Howard students engaging in before the sitting started?

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:41.000
Well, the students were largely engaged in campus issues.

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:44.000
We were concerned with the matter of black studies.

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:47.000
We were concerned with having more younger faculty.

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:50.000
We were concerned with some of the curricula designs.

00:20:50.000 --> 00:21:02.000
And of course we had the other kind of grievances about long lines and inadequate food and lack of participation in faculty tenure decisions.

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:15.000
All of that sort of thing. But the social aspects of what we were engaged in was largely off campus during the years prior to the 60s.

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:26.000
I happened to be selected as a delegate for the University to the United States National Student Association.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:33.000
And that's a confederation of some 500 or more colleges and universities across the country.

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:40.000
And they had annual meetings, they had quarterly meetings, they had various programs.

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:49.000
And one of the programs that I got involved in was the international student relations seminar, Isrus, that was held at Harvard.

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:55.000
And I met students from around the country who were very politically active.

00:21:55.000 --> 00:22:14.000
They were interested in a number of questions like the Liberation of Namibia, South Africa question, the business of the legislation that restricted political expression for getting scholarships from supported by the federal government.

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:21.000
They were very active in some of the labor relations issues on their campuses.

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:27.000
And that exposed me to a different level of political activity than we had at Howard.

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:41.000
And going back to that form year after year also connected me with some of the militants around the country.

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:50.000
I can remember Barney Frank, later the Congressman Frank was an active student member.

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:57.000
One of the guys later became the representative for the National Football League.

00:22:57.000 --> 00:23:06.000
Don Hoffman was active in the student politics and ran for a local office in his home state.

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:10.000
And he was quite an exposure to people.

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:19.000
And one of the exposures was to another subgroup, the students for Democratic society, SDS.

00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:25.000
Ultimately I was deeply involved with the SDS.

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:31.000
And they were very concerned about the issues of being opposed to the war.

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:35.000
They were opposed to the Vietnam activity.

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:41.000
And they were also very militant on the business of draft resistance.

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:48.000
And that exposed me to another more radical dimension of politics.

00:23:48.000 --> 00:24:00.000
At one point toward the end of my term as president, there was of course the sit-in breakout in Greensboro, North Carolina.

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:05.000
And we didn't have a direct role in that.

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:13.000
Although as I mentioned, Paul Emery had been a proponent of integrated lunch counters and back in the 40s.

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:16.000
So there was certainly a tradition there.

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:19.000
Even a broader tradition than just Paul Emery.

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:27.000
Many students were in protests and demonstrations and things downtown against the segregated department stores.

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:32.000
And drinking fountains and other kinds of things.

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:37.000
This is during the 40s and into the 50s.

00:24:37.000 --> 00:24:52.000
In fact, there's a book done by the fellow who's now the dean of students at Yale College.

00:24:52.000 --> 00:25:01.000
John Holloway, Jonathan Holloway, on the history of Howard.

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:04.000
And he deals with three professors.

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:12.000
E. Franklin Frazier, he was a Ralph Bunch.

00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:21.000
And there was a Samuille Harris, the famous economist who went to the University of Caldwell and made a name for himself.

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:35.000
And he talks about in that book the Howard Fervor that was in the faculty during the 40s and 50s.

00:25:35.000 --> 00:25:40.000
And the conflicts that they had with the administration and the border society.

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:54.000
So Howard has a nexus with all aspects of African American political activity, almost from its beginnings.

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:58.000
And so that was reflected in who the faculty were.

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:04.000
And also the kind of issues that were introduced into our studies.

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:12.000
And it involved what the faculty used as their academic focus.

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:16.000
And it was worked through with the entire content.

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:26.000
So in my last year and also my term as a student body president.

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:36.000
The sit-ins erupted and we were asked and approached to support the students who were in the south.

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:48.000
And the student council decided to make a contribution to the legal defense and to the funding of the students who had been arrested.

00:26:48.000 --> 00:27:09.000
And we were confronted by the administration that said that since the student funds were compulsory, that we could not appropriate funds that were compelled contributions from the students to use for political activity that was off campus.

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:12.000
And so we had a big confrontation on that.

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:21.000
And we ultimately, the dean of students for bad, our use of our bank account to support the sit-ins.

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:29.000
Well, we found a little twist around that when the students decided to have a convention in Rolina, Canada.

00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:36.000
We appropriated money to pay for the transportation of the student to go to the convention.

00:27:36.000 --> 00:27:46.000
And also for the hospitality at the convention, which wasn't really a direct expenditure of the students or their direct action.

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:50.000
But it was nevertheless in support of the movement.

00:27:50.000 --> 00:28:01.000
And Dean, Dr. Armagede Blackburn, who was the dean of students at the time, was adamantly opposed to our political involvement.

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:05.000
Fortunately, Mornikai Johnson was president.

00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:13.000
And so we made appeals to him that overruled the vice president for student affairs to allow us to make that expenditure.

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:20.000
So, where are some of the other ways that the sit-in movement affected you or affected powers?

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:29.000
Well, I think it's safe to say, given the timing, I'm graduating in 1960, June 1960.

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:36.000
The sit-in movement started in April in its big manifestation.

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:50.000
Of course, I learned through my participation in the campus chapter of the NAACP, that NAACP chapters had been involved in sit-ins long before 1960.

00:28:50.000 --> 00:29:03.000
And I think that one of the NAACP chairman, Barbara Posey, in Oakland, I believe, was involved in sit-ins.

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:09.000
And we were supporting as a chapter in NAACP the sit-in movement then.

00:29:09.000 --> 00:29:19.000
But that wasn't a campus wide activity until after the 1960s sit-ins became national headlines and national mobilization of students.

00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:29.000
So it's safe to say that there was limited direct involvement in that until after the 60s.

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:40.000
As soon as I, in my graduating year, in fact, the point of my transition from undergrad to graduate,

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:55.000
soakly Carmichael, Cortland Cox, Dionne Diamond, Jean Wheeler, and a number of other students had just been admitted as freshmen at Howard.

00:29:55.000 --> 00:30:05.000
And they were, as you know, stalwarts in the founding of SNCC and the activities of the whole 60s revolution of the South.

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:15.000
So we sort of passed each other to door in the book that Stokely wrote called Ready for Revolution.

00:30:15.000 --> 00:30:18.000
He deals extensively with his Howard experience.

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:26.000
And I think it's a six or 700 page book, but almost a hundred of those pages are devoted to his life at Howard.

00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:34.000
And he talks about the kind of cultural and political contests that he was engaged in.

00:30:34.000 --> 00:30:54.000
But he mentions in a complimentary way the handoff that I had provided for the students when I talked about the need for social activity and relevance and demands and direct action in his book.

00:30:54.000 --> 00:31:09.000
In fact, he made the complimentary mark that when after he listened to the administrators of Howard that he listened to me and he thought I was like a man among boys.

00:31:09.000 --> 00:31:21.000
But my association with the Howard continued after my graduation because the year following my graduation, I was elected.

00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:34.000
The National Affairs Vice President of the United States National Student Association, which involved some 600 or more campuses of which Howard was a member.

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:49.000
So I came back to the campus many times in the capacity of the Vice President National Student Association and had lots of involvement with what was then the new organization called the Nonviolent Action Group,

00:31:49.000 --> 00:32:00.000
which had started on campus to integrate both lunch counters and also amusement parks and other things in the greater Washington area.

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:12.000
So my continuing ties to various people at Howard went beyond my period as an enrolled undergraduate.

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:16.000
Did you attend the Smith Founding Music and Rally?

00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:29.000
You know, that's a question. I have vague recollections of meetings and so many meetings, but I don't think I was at Shaw.

00:32:29.000 --> 00:32:45.000
And there are a couple of reports and books that dispute that, but I don't recall being at Shaw per se, but I quickly got involved in a big way with SNCC while I was National Affairs Vice President.

00:32:46.000 --> 00:32:56.000
While I was National Affairs Vice President, I was also on the Executive Committee of SNCC and the Executive Committee of the Students for Democratic Society.

00:32:56.000 --> 00:33:06.000
And so that again kept me involved in a lot of student activity beyond the period of my undergrad tenure.

00:33:06.000 --> 00:33:12.000
I have a list of participants that the conference will all check and see.

00:33:12.000 --> 00:33:15.000
Yeah, I don't think you'll find me there.

00:33:15.000 --> 00:33:35.000
You told me in the past that when you were fit in your involvement with the US National Student Association, that you were actually initially interested in being Vice President for the International Affairs, and that you were sort of maneuvered into?

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:45.000
Well, my introduction and original fascination and preoccupation with National Student Association was through its International Arm.

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:55.000
I had gotten involved in what I mentioned, the Icerus, the International Student Relations Seminar, and I had participated in the delegation that went to Cuba.

00:33:55.000 --> 00:34:10.000
I had gone, hosted the students from Africa, Caribbean, in the United States, and I had a real focus on International Affairs.

00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:21.000
And it was my intent when I went to the final Congress as a student to run for the International Affairs Vice President.

00:34:22.000 --> 00:34:34.000
I had did not know at the time that there was a heavy involvement from the CIA in the International Arm of National Student Association.

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:41.000
They had, in fact, this International Student Relations Seminar, after participating in the Harvard, was funded by the CIA.

00:34:41.000 --> 00:34:44.000
I didn't know it at the time. It wasn't certainly not disclosed.

00:34:45.000 --> 00:35:05.000
But the people who were the CIA operatives who were also involved in the staff and advisors for the National Student Association, were very concerned that a person with my connections with the South and with the Middle Tennessee and with the Civil Rights Movement,

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:26.000
and through the previous chairmanship with the local chapter in WACP, and so on, could not be trusted to keep the confidentiality agreement that existed between International Affairs Officers and the National Student Association and the CIA.

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:50.000
So, at the convention when I was actively campaigning for International Affairs Vice President, they did an maneuver to prevent my selection by getting the convention to name me a National Affairs Vice President by acclimation.

00:35:51.000 --> 00:36:16.000
So, I was not elected in the normal channels. I was preempted in my effort to become international affairs by this group of National Student Association alumnus, many of which were, in fact, CIA agents, after they were, maybe during, but certainly after they were 10 years as officers of the National Student Association.

00:36:16.000 --> 00:36:37.000
So, that's how became National Affairs Vice President. But fortunately, that was when the sit-ins were in their explosion. So, I was in a much more influential and important position as National Affairs Vice President, and I ever could have been as International Affairs Vice President.

00:36:37.000 --> 00:36:40.000
So, faith has a way of working things out.

00:36:41.000 --> 00:36:56.000
I know that the US NSA had their annual Congresses, that was its call, in Minneapolis in some of 1960, and there was a debate about whether or not to support the Southern cities.

00:36:57.000 --> 00:37:15.000
Oh, that was a constant issue. The National Student Association has a policy of basic policy declarations and individual resolutions that are adopted by the assembled group at their national conventions called Congresses.

00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:28.000
And for a long period of time, since Brown versus Board of Education, they had been taking positions on integration and issues of integrated education in particular.

00:37:28.000 --> 00:37:44.000
And this was strongly resisted by the component of the membership that was sub-ent, places like Clemson, the University of Alabama, Texas, A&M, all those schools were members of the National Student Association.

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:55.000
And they protested what they called politicizing, which should be just strictly student and educational issues and getting involved in another thing.

00:37:55.000 --> 00:38:11.000
Well, it succeeded to get the resolutions passed every year on education, but with the sit-ins, it was a bit of a departure from strictly educational subject matter to deal with social integration.

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:29.000
And so there was a walk out of Southern schools protesting that. And I, of course, got involved in that because we were supporting resolution in support of the sit-in movement.

00:38:29.000 --> 00:38:36.000
That resolution passed, and we lost the large number of Southern schools as members as a result of that.

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:54.000
We also had issues because during the time that I was a national affairs vice president, that was the beginning of the young Berger movement in the collegiate community.

00:38:54.000 --> 00:39:07.000
The Bergers were the youthful offshoot of the John Berger society and the presidential election with the gold water.

00:39:07.000 --> 00:39:16.000
There was a tremendous right-wing student element in the United States. They called themselves the young Americans for freedom.

00:39:16.000 --> 00:39:34.000
They were very vocal. Many of the people who now are in the anti-abortion movement and shutting down the plan. Some of those same names are some of the people who were in the Yaffe movement in the student days.

00:39:34.000 --> 00:39:56.000
And so that became a major confrontation of what to do with the Yaffe. It culminated in my case in a particular incident when Yaffe invited Bill Buckley to be a speaker at their side convention.

00:39:56.000 --> 00:40:13.000
They tried to get him as a speaker for the Congress itself, and of course we resisted that. But they had a parallel meeting that was adjacent to the campus that we were meeting on and invited Bill Buckley to speak.

00:40:13.000 --> 00:40:30.000
And after Bill Buckley spoke, I gave a rebuttal of what he had to say and accused him of being a slave owning fascist mentality, which made the Yaffe people go ballistic.

00:40:30.000 --> 00:40:45.000
And they introduced a resolution to censor me saying that I had abused my authority as National Fair's Vice President to speak on a political issue and without authorization and no resolution is supporting.

00:40:45.000 --> 00:41:08.000
And we had a big conflict arose and we ultimately had a vote on this motion for censorship. And during that time we were able to expose all of the right wing ideology and how it affect educational policy, international policy, political policy, military policy, etc.

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:21.000
And I have a recording in the records of that debate. And ultimately the resolution to censor me was defeated. And I was able to continue my career as National Fair's Vice President.

00:41:21.000 --> 00:41:45.000
But the politics of the right wing were just beginning to take shape. And the virtues that we now see as the Trump supporters were just beginning to organize and test their muscles. And the National Student Association became one of the forms which that clash was revealed.

00:41:45.000 --> 00:42:06.000
So one of the things that I know that during that year that you were National Fair's Vice President, you were very active in the sit-ins and supporting SNCC and bringing students and various groups together. One of the people that was also central was Elebaker. Do you remember how you met Elebaker? Can you describe us for us?

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:35.000
Well, Elebaker was kind of a great eminence in the world of civil rights for a long period of time. Of course, long before we were involved. She had been initially associated with the Pullman Car Porters and was a confidante and friend of a Philip Randolph and had supported his call early on for March on Washington back in the 40s and 50s.

00:42:36.000 --> 00:42:54.000
She was instrumental in the management and operation and founding of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference and she was an official on their staff. She was prominent in the YWCA movement.

00:42:54.000 --> 00:43:08.000
The YWCA movement was really a shelter for a lot of militant blacks in the 30s and 40s because with the label Christian they were able to do a lot of political activity without being attacked.

00:43:08.000 --> 00:43:18.000
And so she had grown up in that kind of organized labor and civil rights and community service environment.

00:43:19.000 --> 00:43:41.000
She was adopted as an advisor to SNCC and people particularly in Atlanta had become familiar with the YWCA where she was employed, had an office in Atlanta and became very close to some of the SNCC movers and shakers.

00:43:41.000 --> 00:43:55.000
Well, she became the kind of godmother of SNCC and my association with her grew as I got more and more involved in SNCC activity.

00:43:55.000 --> 00:44:20.000
I was surprised to see when looking at some of my old records that the meeting that was held of the SNCC executive committee in December after the founding of SNCC was held at the Butler Street Y in Atlanta and when I read the minutes I was surprised to see that I was cheering it.

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:32.000
That was the meeting of which Mary and Barry was replaced by a believed either Chuck McDew. I think with Chuck McDew became the next chairman of SNCC.

00:44:32.000 --> 00:44:49.000
So that put me in interface with Ella Baker in a really special way and she's of course risen in the world's eyes as one of the matriarchs of the modern civil rights movement.

00:44:50.000 --> 00:45:04.000
And one of the things that happened that year that you were US NSA vice president was the Freedom Rides. Were you ever tempted to join the Freedom Rides?

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:20.000
No, I wouldn't say that I was tempted to join the Freedom Rides came a little after my, I was no longer an undergraduate, I was no longer a national vice president really because the Freedom Rides came in 61.

00:45:20.000 --> 00:45:43.000
My term was the academic year from 60 to 61. So I was leaving NSA at that time and then enrolling in law school. I had a number of friends who of course I had met in the movement in the SNCC meetings and also at Howard who were participating in the Freedom Rides.

00:45:43.000 --> 00:45:55.000
But I never was directly involved in the Freedom Rides except to engage in fundraising and other kinds of support in the North for what they were doing in the South.

00:45:55.000 --> 00:46:11.000
And of course one of the interesting things was I was at Howard, I'm sorry at Yale and William Sloan coffin, the chaplain at Yale participated in Freedom Rises as you know.

00:46:11.000 --> 00:46:37.000
And was one of the historic figures there. And of course I interrelated with the, with the, the, Bill coffin many times. I, in fact, was sent on funds that he raised from the Connecticut chapter of the Women's League for Peace and Freedom to support

00:46:37.000 --> 00:47:05.000
the, uh, uh, uh, uh, uh, make your ever's widow after his assassination. So my continuation with civil rights went into my law school years in a heavy way. And I was one of the, uh, principal circuit speakers to raise funds along with the, um, the, uh, Freedom singers.

00:47:05.000 --> 00:47:30.000
Uh, in, uh, in all of the campuses of the United States because having been national fairs vice president, I had contacts who were current officers of student organizations around the country and was able to open their doors as supporters and as forums for a student activist to come and lecture and speak.

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:43.000
I know that one of the things that was going on in the summer of 1961 was a debate and snick about whether to focus on direct action or whether to move in the, in the direction of voter registration and political power.

00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:52.000
And I know that you were sort of a central figure in that debate or that discussion. Can you describe that in some of what was going on that summer?

00:47:52.000 --> 00:48:04.000
Uh, I think it's important to appreciate that there was a kind of division of emphasis in the SNCC membership.

00:48:04.000 --> 00:48:32.000
There had been from the beginning a religious contingent of SNCC people who largely were influenced by the teachings of Jim Lawson and they tended to be associated with the Nashville student community.

00:48:32.000 --> 00:48:44.000
The Diane Nash and, um, Marion also came from that Nashville environment, um, Jim Bevel and others.

00:48:44.000 --> 00:48:54.000
And their orientation to student, to direct action was as a religious expression.

00:48:54.000 --> 00:49:06.000
Their notion was that they were doing something that was consistent with their Christian ethic and that the non-violence was also part of it because that was the Christian way to do things.

00:49:06.000 --> 00:49:18.000
Well, there were others who were interested in the objection, in the objective of integration, but didn't come to the question from a religious perspective.

00:49:18.000 --> 00:49:31.000
They came with a greater interest in the politics of it and concerned with the social change as a business of the exercise of civic responsibility and prerogative.

00:49:31.000 --> 00:49:48.000
And so, at a given point, the people who were the religious contingent were insisting that they be paramount in the ideology of SNCC.

00:49:48.000 --> 00:50:15.000
At an early stage, there was a question of what the name of the organization would be and it was agreed that it would be the student coordinating committee and the people from Nashville insisted that non-violent be added to the name as a way to distinguish it from other kinds of student organizations like students for democratic society and non-instudent and other kinds of things.

00:50:15.000 --> 00:50:37.000
Well, at a given point, the dichotomy of objectives became so pronounced that there was a fear of the organization splitting along the lines of the religious oriented and the secular oriented.

00:50:37.000 --> 00:50:53.000
And of course, I was in the secular side of that question. And Ella Baker was instrumental in harmonizing the two diverging interests.

00:50:53.000 --> 00:51:16.000
And there's a letter that she wrote to me in my years as a National Affairs Vice President urging that SNCC not have this difference that would be disruptive to the ultimate purpose.

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:36.000
So that was a real expression of her influence that was critical for the survival of SNCC. And of course, during that whole period, she was very supportive of the kinds of efforts that we were trying to do with political voter registration as the real method of change.

00:51:36.000 --> 00:51:51.000
It was my view and I think it was shared by Charles Charade, Charles McDoug and Charles Jones as the three charges that supported the approach of politics over religion.

00:51:51.000 --> 00:52:01.000
And we were adamant that you could not really change the South unless you changed the politics.

00:52:01.000 --> 00:52:15.000
That all that business of weight-ins and sit-ins and pray-ins were fine from a cosmetic point of view, but it didn't alter the status and the political situation of black people.

00:52:15.000 --> 00:52:25.000
That was only going to be altered when you took the control of the organs of state. Because the organs of state determined who the police chief was.

00:52:25.000 --> 00:52:36.000
The organs of state determined which roads were going to be paved. The organs of state determined what the budget was going to be in college and in primary and secondary school.

00:52:36.000 --> 00:52:53.000
The organs of state determined who was going to have access to public employment. And unless you took control of the organs of state, you would be out there as beggars, not as really determinants of the right in a material way.

00:52:53.000 --> 00:53:09.000
So from our point of view, voting was the key. We borrowed the Nekrumas and Komeyum from the New Testament, the Seakey first, the political rights and all the rest shall be added unto you.

00:53:09.000 --> 00:53:20.000
And we thought that the political rights were more important than the spiritual rights that were in housed and sit-in movement.

00:53:20.000 --> 00:53:32.000
So the direct action campaign and the voting rights campaign also were competitive on resources. Who were the groups that would support which?

00:53:32.000 --> 00:53:36.000
And so that became another aspect of the contest between.

00:53:36.000 --> 00:53:48.000
And that same summer you're meeting with other people, meeting with Perry Bale-Hontay and members of the Kennedy administration about this question too.

00:53:48.000 --> 00:54:17.000
Well, there was a kind of focus meeting that was held at the Kappa Hosek, Virginia, in which the Kennedy administration operatives were seeking to influence the direction of the movement to emphasize the business of political as opposed to confrontational street.

00:54:17.000 --> 00:54:39.000
That was really motivated for two points of view. One, the street demonstrations were volatile. They frequently erupted or were provoked violence and they were unpredictable.

00:54:39.000 --> 00:54:57.000
And the voter campaign also had more statutory and constitutional justification for federal involvement than some of these other social things.

00:54:57.000 --> 00:55:09.000
And so they were interested in procuring a more orderly political protest.

00:55:09.000 --> 00:55:22.000
Well, their interest coincided with our interest from our perspective because unless and until we had political rights the others would not be secure.

00:55:22.000 --> 00:55:31.000
So we were interested in promoting voting as a primary thrust because we saw that as the real engine for change.

00:55:31.000 --> 00:55:46.000
Now historians have distorted that and some have characterized even our good friend Howard Zinn as something that we were co-opted by the Kennedy administration to go away from demonstrations. That's not correct.

00:55:46.000 --> 00:55:53.000
We were co-opted if anything we were co-opting them to become supporters and invest in what we wanted to do.

00:55:53.000 --> 00:56:06.000
Branded they had a political interest as well if they could change the South that they could have more blacks voting, if they blacks who voted were more democratic and oriented to their politics that would be a gain for them.

00:56:06.000 --> 00:56:18.000
But that was very secondary to anything we were concerned with. We didn't care whether they voted Republicans or Democrats. We wanted them to be able to vote so their voices would be heard.

00:56:18.000 --> 00:56:27.000
And if the administration was prepared to support getting us the right to vote then we were prepared to invite their support in every way we could,

00:56:27.000 --> 00:56:34.000
and we were politically and of course through the powers of the courts.

00:56:34.000 --> 00:56:54.000
That was the nature of the relationship and we had this sort of culminating meeting in the Capohosic Virginia and that brought together the assistant attorney general for civil rights,

00:56:54.000 --> 00:57:08.000
who was the special assistant to the president and Burke Marshall who was to become the assistant attorney general for civil rights.

00:57:08.000 --> 00:57:23.000
This was a kind of seminal meeting that launched an integrated comprehensive, south wide voter education campaign.

00:57:23.000 --> 00:57:34.000
And at that conference we had Charlie Jones, Charles Surrod and Charles McDoug as participant as was I.

00:57:34.000 --> 00:57:52.000
And it was at that time that we established the foundations of a relationship with the operatives and the justice department in the White House in support of what we wanted to do and the day of course wanted to give support to the political change of the South as well.

00:57:52.000 --> 00:58:18.000
I know that one of the points of contention at least for a few people I think Diane Nash I read her comments on this that one of the things on the table was how the Kennedy administration would handle the drafting of the young men working on voter registration and she felt that that might be a way of manipulating people if they were going to defer draft.

00:58:18.000 --> 00:58:30.000
Well one of the peculiarities of draft machinery is that they are local drafting boards.

00:58:30.000 --> 00:58:43.000
There's not a national drafting board per se. Those are locally determined and the people who sit on those local draft boards are usually the nominees of the elected officials.

00:58:44.000 --> 00:59:00.000
So the draft board of Mississippi reflects the politicians of Mississippi and they have the prerogative within the range of statues to select people and to go after people to draft people based on their own motives.

00:59:00.000 --> 00:59:15.000
And of course they did use that authority to target SNCC activists and other civil rights activists to get them off the streets and put them away for a couple of three years.

00:59:15.000 --> 00:59:27.000
In fact one of the organizations that I was associated with later took on that issue. It was the national conference of black lawyers and CBL.

00:59:27.000 --> 00:59:50.000
And during my career as a lawyer in the trenches one of the issues we went after was the improper use by General Hershey who was then the head of whatever the formal title of the registration effort.

00:59:50.000 --> 01:00:06.000
He was going after SNCC people with the vengeance. And we even had one case where they went after one of our students activists and imprisoned him.

01:00:06.000 --> 01:00:20.000
Even though the statute said that the enforcement of the draft was only pertaining to people under 23 years of age and he was more than 23 years of age.

01:00:20.000 --> 01:00:34.000
We ultimately took that to the court and got it thrown out. But that just showed that clearly the administration was not using all of its muscle to support what we wanted to do.

01:00:34.000 --> 01:01:01.000
It was manifested also in a more direct way in the voting registration question. And that's where I think SNCC made some of its major contributions because we succeeded in the testimony on the voting rights act to force the administration to amend their draft to include a provision that said that voting rights cases will be heard by a three judge court not by a single judge.

01:01:01.000 --> 01:01:17.000
And that was critical. The whole voting rights act would have had no life in the Mississippi, Alabama, Georgia, South Carolina, Louisiana if the judges that were appointed by the senators of those states were making those decisions.

01:01:17.000 --> 01:01:41.000
So we made the determination that we needed a provision to create an exception in voting rights cases so that they would not be tried by a single sitting judge but rather be a three judge panel with two of three named by the chief judge of the Court of Appeals.

01:01:41.000 --> 01:02:01.000
That was strategic because the Supreme Court had made clear that the whole business of the selection of the, I've lost my thought.

01:02:01.000 --> 01:02:21.000
The business of the selection of judges was a political question and not a legal question. And that meant that the political process had to solve it. The only way we could get a political process to solve was to have three judges because then the Court of Appeals would name the judges.

01:02:21.000 --> 01:02:37.000
And as politics would have it, most of the judges of the Court of Appeals had been appointed by Eisenhower and they were Republicans and they were interested in allowing blacks to vote.

01:02:37.000 --> 01:02:54.000
And therefore, when the chief judge of the Fifth Circuit, which covered most of the Southern states, made appointments, he would put two sympathetic judges on the panel with one unsympathetic judge and that allowed us to win most of those cases.

01:02:54.000 --> 01:03:04.000
Well, that becomes part of the sophisticated way in which we were both allied and opposed to the Kennedy administration.

01:03:04.000 --> 01:03:14.000
Because Kennedy was really not interested in supporting that three judge court. He opposed it in the testimony before the House Judiciary Committee.

01:03:14.000 --> 01:03:33.000
And we succeeded in convincing Chairman Scheller from New York to go with us. And frankly, we got Republicans on the House Judiciary Committee to vote with us to overwhelm the Democrats from the South who voted against them.

01:03:33.000 --> 01:03:43.000
So the politics of this is sophisticated and beyond the normal black and white of we were supporting Kennedy, we weren't supporting him, he was supporting us.

01:03:43.000 --> 01:03:55.000
It was more subtle than that. It gets down to the fine granulations of where the interests lie and partisan politics is sometimes irrelevant to racial politics.

01:03:55.000 --> 01:04:00.000
And Snick was then in for racial politics and not for partisan politics.

01:04:00.000 --> 01:04:13.000
I know one of the other things that you did that summer of 1961 was raise the money and organize a seminar. I can't remember what was the formal name of the seminar in Nashville.

01:04:13.000 --> 01:04:27.000
Oh, well, what I was really trying to do in Nashville was replicate the little form experience that I had had at Howard.

01:04:27.000 --> 01:04:51.000
It was clear to me from interacting with the students who were the leadership of the sit-in movement that they had no exposure to the questions of black history, civil rights struggle, racial conflict, constitutional context, international implications,

01:04:51.000 --> 01:05:00.000
because they were raised in an educational system that forbade that kind of exposure and information.

01:05:00.000 --> 01:05:20.000
So what I wanted to do was I wanted to have a kind of cram course to invite the leaders of the sit-in movement to sit down with some of the top minds who were knowledgeable on the racial implications of politics.

01:05:20.000 --> 01:05:28.000
So I wanted to have a kind of background in the political and political and political discussions of politics, economic, sociology, and learn.

01:05:28.000 --> 01:05:40.000
And that was the seminar that I put together. It was supported by the New World Foundation, the Teconic Foundation. It may have had some Ford money.

01:05:40.000 --> 01:05:54.000
Dr. King, he wrote a letter of support, Ella Baker in the two-page letter that was later republished in a recent conference.

01:05:54.000 --> 01:06:06.000
She supported it and she supported the concept of bringing together the whole SNCC mechanism to do the voter registration thing in a major way.

01:06:06.000 --> 01:06:34.000
And that conference, I call the first Freedom School, because it was the first time many of these students who were in the South had ever been exposed to that kind of saturated black history and history of political struggle and the history of racism in America.

01:06:34.000 --> 01:06:42.000
So I celebrate that seminar as one of the few places that I had a chance to touch the pages of history.

01:06:42.000 --> 01:06:50.000
I always point that seminar to my students when they're interested in protest.

01:06:50.000 --> 01:07:00.000
That in actually scope the Carmichael chapter on Howard and the intersection of education and protest in a meaningful way.

01:07:00.000 --> 01:07:19.000
It's kind of speaking of scope the Carmichael. It's kind of interesting because in many ways your orientation is towards the political end of things and the seminar is located in Nashville, which is the stronghold of the more religious direct action phase in the Civil Rights Movement.

01:07:19.000 --> 01:07:30.000
And both the Carmichael rates and his memoir about that seminar getting in trouble because of his involvement in one of the demonstrations that came along with that.

01:07:30.000 --> 01:07:35.000
I don't know if you remember any of those comments or all or not.

01:07:35.000 --> 01:07:37.000
I'm not going to be able to talk about that.

01:07:37.000 --> 01:07:42.000
I'm certain you know the seminar, but I don't know if a particular demonstration as a sidebar to that.

01:07:42.000 --> 01:07:50.000
He said they were doing some demonstration in downtown Nashville. He got in trouble for not being explicitly non-violent in every way.

01:07:50.000 --> 01:07:53.000
But that's sort of the distraction.

01:07:53.000 --> 01:08:11.000
But we selected the Nashville because they have historically had a thing called the Race Relations Institute, which goes way back to the 30s and have a long and celebrated history of bringing blacks and whites and thinkers to the world.

01:08:11.000 --> 01:08:15.000
And thinkers together to talk about issues of race.

01:08:15.000 --> 01:08:29.000
So it really made sense from a historic perspective to hold our seminar in the cradle of Fisk University, which was the sponsor of the Race Relations Institute historically.

01:08:29.000 --> 01:08:32.000
So that's why we ended up at Nashville.

01:08:32.000 --> 01:08:39.000
Wasn't because we were there by the religious persuasion of Jim Lawson or Diane Nash or others.

01:08:39.000 --> 01:08:44.000
This is sort of educational mission and history there.

01:08:44.000 --> 01:08:58.000
Were you at, do you have memories of the Highland Remedies in August 1961 where this debate kind of came to a head of the direct action and the voter registration and elevator pound full things together?

01:08:58.000 --> 01:09:03.000
Well, there were so many meetings that it's hard for me to distinguish one from the other.

01:09:03.000 --> 01:09:09.000
We had many meetings where that happened and many of them were held at Highlander.

01:09:09.000 --> 01:09:25.000
And Highlander was a favorable place to be uninterrupted out in the woods so we could eat and sleep with the subject matter and not be disturbed.

01:09:25.000 --> 01:09:36.000
So I can't even distinguish a single Highlander meeting because I was in and out of Highlander all the time and we were always meeting on the same subjects of civil rights.

01:09:36.000 --> 01:09:52.000
So that reminds me there was a letter that you shared recently and you told me about, I think it was leaving Highlander and you and Elevator were in a car with a group of people and it was an accident?

01:09:52.000 --> 01:10:03.000
Well, it was really an attempt to injure us more than an accident. It was a provocative act of violence.

01:10:03.000 --> 01:10:13.000
We were going from Highlander Folk School which is in Montego, Tennessee to the airport in Chaleneuga.

01:10:13.000 --> 01:10:22.000
And along the way we were riding in one of these little boxy Volkswagen buses.

01:10:22.000 --> 01:10:37.000
And we were in there singing and doing our normal movement stuff and this 10 wheeler, 8 wheeler truck came along with a driver who saw that was an integrated group.

01:10:37.000 --> 01:10:43.000
And he pushed us off the highway and as you know that's the Chaleneuga Mountains.

01:10:43.000 --> 01:11:01.000
And there's a very rough steep places and we almost went crashing over and down into the ravine below but for being stopped by a tree that happened to be between us and the bottom.

01:11:01.000 --> 01:11:11.000
And we sat for quite a bit of time rocking back and forth such that if we shifted our weight too much to one side or the other we would have gone down.

01:11:11.000 --> 01:11:23.000
And fortunately before we went down a pickup truck was mobilized and came and hooked the front of our bus and pulled us out of that ravine.

01:11:23.000 --> 01:11:36.000
Elbeger was done a person who particularly emphasized her religious tenants.

01:11:36.000 --> 01:11:46.000
In fact she was very skeptical of having seen ministers up close for a long period of time about the ethics and importance of what they were really doing.

01:11:47.000 --> 01:11:54.000
And she used to always ridicule the statement that she learned as a child.

01:11:54.000 --> 01:12:06.000
Thank God for Jesus and she used to toy with us and say, now what does that mean? How could that have any meaning? What significance do they mean? Thank God for Jesus.

01:12:06.000 --> 01:12:21.000
Well after we had this incident in the Cumberland Mountains and the tow truck pulled us out before we had slipped down to the ravine.

01:12:22.000 --> 01:12:34.000
Elbeger when she was on her stretcher being taken to the ambulance motion for me to come close to her and I did and she said thank God for Jesus.

01:12:35.000 --> 01:12:52.000
I've seen some letters back there where she expressed a desire to be part of a freedom ride but that she said after this accident and getting her head she didn't think it was probably the best use of her time.

01:12:53.000 --> 01:13:01.000
And the other work that needed to be done but also she probably shouldn't offer up her head to the segregation.

01:13:01.000 --> 01:13:21.000
And I never knew the context of that accident and that fall you started school at Yale, law school at Yale and at the same time SNCC moves into the comb for the registration project at the end of that summer.

01:13:21.000 --> 01:13:29.000
What was your motivation or your thinking about why you entered law school?

01:13:29.000 --> 01:13:33.000
Well there were two prongs.

01:13:34.000 --> 01:13:55.000
One was the business of having some skills for ultimate career and to have skills that were relevant to social change that would be meaningful as opposed to peripheral.

01:13:55.000 --> 01:14:22.000
And the second was part of our scheme to make sure that we had some people who survived during what could have been a disaster either through murder, incarceration or the draft.

01:14:23.000 --> 01:14:44.000
And our fear was that all of the SNCC people could be wiped out in an overnight event if we were all vulnerable located in the South in our various projects.

01:14:44.000 --> 01:14:55.000
So the suggestion was made that maybe we should have some who would be out of the reach of those disasters.

01:14:55.000 --> 01:15:12.000
And I might be a good candidate for that and going ahead with the enrolling at Yale and New Haven where I would be have a student's exemption where we certainly wouldn't have any violent question.

01:15:12.000 --> 01:15:28.000
And I could be useful in continuing to mobilize white campuses as supporters and to continue to get volunteers from those campuses to go to the South for various stints of time.

01:15:28.000 --> 01:15:37.000
Either for the summer project in Mississippi or the other things of voter registration in some of the rural areas of Mississippi Alabama, Georgia and South Carolina.

01:15:37.000 --> 01:15:55.000
And so I went to law school with that dual purpose of sort of being like a Shagavara in the year of Madras that would come back to re-establish SNCC if it had been wiped out.

01:15:55.000 --> 01:16:07.000
On the other hand, going and getting a set of degrees that would be helpful to the long term movement and the thirdly to be a northern voice for SNCC.

01:16:07.000 --> 01:16:21.000
And I did organize concert tours for the Freedom Singers and many speaking engagements that all of those campuses from New Hampshire, on down to Pennsylvania, New York.

01:16:21.000 --> 01:16:43.000
So it served multiple purposes to be at the law school. And of course being at the law school also gave me another set of professional contacts and mobilizers for SNCC, William Sloan-Koffam, who was the chaplain at Yale, was ultimately recruited to be a freedom rider.

01:16:43.000 --> 01:16:58.000
And that's no accident. And he also brought another colleague of his from Old Westbury to be part of it too and Wesley and University in Connecticut.

01:16:58.000 --> 01:17:19.000
So being in New Haven was really an northern adjunct to SNCC. And it was at New Haven that I came to know Peter Countryman and Joan Countryman, who started a thing called the Northern Student Movement.

01:17:19.000 --> 01:17:37.000
And the Northern Student Movement was designed to do in the north exactly what we were doing in the south. And the Northern Student Movement was one of the unsung heroes of that whole era. And I was able to do that having met them in New Haven.

01:17:37.000 --> 01:17:44.000
So New Haven had a lot of fallout both for me personally and for I think the movement.

01:17:44.000 --> 01:17:50.000
What are some of the things that you think are significant about the Northern Student Movement as an unsung hero?

01:17:50.000 --> 01:18:12.000
Well the fact that they got people who would take a year off from school and instead of going to Paris or Heidelberg or someplace or the Rome, that they would go to the south and spend a dedicated period of time working with poor people.

01:18:12.000 --> 01:18:24.000
That they would teach schools, freedom schools, they would create health clinics, that they would create again social organizations. And the Northern Student Movement was not alone.

01:18:24.000 --> 01:18:40.000
There was the young Christian students, YCS, which did similar things and before it turned more political, the SDS, students for democratic society.

01:18:40.000 --> 01:19:09.000
There were several satellite student organizations which were non-Sovent, which were critical to the success of what was happening in the south. And the communications were facilitated by the fact that they had an organizational corpus that was independently funded and also able to be supportive and auxiliary to what SNCC was doing.

01:19:09.000 --> 01:19:17.000
And Northern Student Movement was perhaps the most prominent of those dedicated to the question of civil rights alone.

01:19:17.000 --> 01:19:38.000
In fall 61, when SNCC is working in Macomb and then extends to some of the surrounding areas, I guess, part of the voter registration push that you're a part of who connects with Bob Moses, who would come to voter registration by way of

01:19:38.000 --> 01:19:48.000
fellow baker and Kim Zimor and kind of meet up in Macomb.

01:19:48.000 --> 01:19:49.000
You know something to show?

01:19:49.000 --> 01:20:18.000
Well, there's this letter that the elder baker sent to me. They did June 21, 1961. And in that letter, she introduces me to Bob Moses and to Amzy Moore and to a number of other people who ultimately were the backbone of the voter registration.

01:20:18.000 --> 01:20:45.000
And of course, that voter registration focus on Macomb was one that we contrived to be a kind of catalyst for a statewide effort. And we chose Macomb because it was very rural, very isolated and nobody else wanted it.

01:20:45.000 --> 01:21:05.000
In the competition for funds for voter registration, the NAACP wanted Atlanta, SCLC wanted Montgomery, the core wanted Louis Viana and New Orleans and Bogalusa.

01:21:05.000 --> 01:21:26.000
Nobody wanted Macomb. But SNCC thought it important to go into one of the most hostile and remote areas of the movement and make a beachhead there that could be a model for the rest of the South.

01:21:26.000 --> 01:21:47.000
And that's how we ended up with Macomb as a designated place. Of course, we also had to do the good offices of the elder baker and Anzy Moore and Bob Moses contacts of people in those areas that would house us and allow us to come and operate.

01:21:47.000 --> 01:22:12.000
Macomb had another unique asset and it was a building that the police would not touch. It had a Masonic's lodge that was there in Macomb, Black Masonic's lodge, which had a history of militant behavior and immunity from police violence.

01:22:12.000 --> 01:22:36.000
I don't know what it is with its Masonic brotherhood or what have you. But for some reason, Masonic lodges became housing for much of SNCC in Jackson and other places because there seemed to be a seven white abhorns about defiling a Masonic lodge.

01:22:36.000 --> 01:22:52.000
So we found once we found that out, where are we going to hold our meetings? We're going to hold our meetings at the Masonic's lodge. And so they had a fine facility there in the Masonic lodge that allowed us to mobilize our movement quite successful.

01:22:52.000 --> 01:23:15.000
There's an anecdote that I should tell you that when we were traveling down from Chicago to Macomb for the very beginning of our effort there, we drove through Alabama and we had an experience in a little city called Deal.

01:23:16.000 --> 01:23:33.000
Chuck McDew, Charles Sharad and Charlie Jones and I were driving in this old gelopy. And in Deal, we hit this dog that ran out between two parked cars.

01:23:34.000 --> 01:23:51.000
And on the heels of that incident, this lady, elderly white lady, started complaining and screaming in the street that we had killed her dog and that she wanted compensation for it.

01:23:52.000 --> 01:24:07.000
And this crowd was beginning to form around the car. And the question was, were we going to pay how much we were going to pay or what were we going to pay. And we divided Chuck McDew and I didn't want to pay anything.

01:24:07.000 --> 01:24:36.000
Charlie Jones and Charlie Sharad wanted to pay something. And while we were in the midst of this and the crowd was getting more and more hostile and starting to close in on us, this elderly man with white linen suit and one of those fine-fed straw hats came down from a porch that was adjacent to the accident scene.

01:24:38.000 --> 01:24:56.000
And he obviously was a figure of authority in the community because they cleared a path for him as he came to the crowd. And he said, I saw the whole thing and there was nothing these boys could have done to avoid hitting that dog.

01:24:57.000 --> 01:25:07.000
And they didn't have any way that they could possibly keep out of the path that they were in because there are cars on both sides.

01:25:09.000 --> 01:25:22.000
And that quelled the crowd. And then he turned to us and said, I don't know how long. Keep these underbitches quiet.

01:25:23.000 --> 01:25:38.000
Yo boys, did he get out of here? We drove from there without a stop from Dio Al Dama to Mississippi. And was the first time in my life I was glad to see a science and welcome to the Magnolia State.

01:25:39.000 --> 01:25:45.000
You never know how it's going to go.

01:25:48.000 --> 01:25:55.000
So, McComb, what was your assessment of McComb and the work in McComb at the time?

01:25:56.000 --> 01:26:09.000
Well, I guess the best thing I can say about McComb is that it's still there. I mean, it's still going. Students are vitally involved in the history of civil rights. They're doing student projects.

01:26:09.000 --> 01:26:18.000
They have engaged in the local school in creating a stable part of a black history in their curricula.

01:26:19.000 --> 01:26:31.000
They have youngsters who have taken time to devote themselves for summers on this. They have scholarship programs to get some of the McComb students into higher education.

01:26:31.000 --> 01:26:39.000
And the local community hasn't just withered at the termination of our particular project.

01:26:40.000 --> 01:26:55.000
The local people in McComb are still there. And they're still advocating for their rights. And very importantly, they're passing on to the next generation of youngsters the lessons of yesterday.

01:26:56.000 --> 01:27:09.000
And so I think McComb really represents a high point in our efforts because we established the beachhead in the rural and most backward corner of the country that is still survived.

01:27:14.000 --> 01:27:20.000
Teaching for change has been an institutional arm to make McComb real.

01:27:21.000 --> 01:27:28.000
Teaching for change, of course, is an organization that tries to do that Broadway across many different places.

01:27:28.000 --> 01:27:41.000
But the McComb project has been kind of a poster child for the success that can come from working with school teachers and with parents in local communities.

01:27:42.000 --> 01:27:58.000
And to make them feel that they can change the direction of the education of their kids by having them understand more deeply the importance of history and the social engagement that the community had, not just the schools.

01:27:59.000 --> 01:28:09.000
One of the things that happened as part of the McComb movement is that those moved in to some of the surroundings and more world communities.

01:28:09.000 --> 01:28:24.000
And in the process, one of the people that was helping him, Herbert Lee, was murdered by state representative. What was it like to be in your early planning and dealing with life and death?

01:28:25.000 --> 01:28:41.000
Well, I particularly point to that Herbert Lee story as a teaching tool in mobilization of black voters throughout the state.

01:28:42.000 --> 01:28:55.000
I found one of the old WBAI recordings of a speech I gave in I guess 62 or 63 in Holmes County.

01:28:55.000 --> 01:29:07.000
And the focal point of that discussion was the business of the Herbert Lee story and the importance of not letting Herbert Lee die in vain.

01:29:08.000 --> 01:29:24.000
Of course, Bob Moses in his own saintly way has had a tremendous influence and all of the details of how that influence has been felt are still not fully known.

01:29:24.000 --> 01:29:46.000
But certainly his willingness to go out and live among the people in a really intellectual gorilla, if you will, to create a, and from a grounds up movement of people who demand change is the symbol of what the organization teaching for change is trying to do.

01:29:46.000 --> 01:29:56.000
It's trying to introduce through the vehicle of public education, the means by which self help in the community can be mobilized.

01:29:56.000 --> 01:30:11.000
And what we've done in teaching for change is to have a website that does that teaching for change.org connected with the civil rights veterans organization, the one,

01:30:11.000 --> 01:30:27.000
one, one vote, or one vote, snake, I forget which, that, or all techniques to make sure this experience isn't lost and doesn't cease to be replicated in other communities around the country.

01:30:27.000 --> 01:30:41.000
Of course, Bob Moses influence in the whole of Mississippi is a part of a legend that is yet to be fully explored and told.

01:30:41.000 --> 01:30:55.000
I know that I saw a documentary maybe a year or so ago at the launch for the civil rights history project website about Greenwood Mississippi.

01:30:55.000 --> 01:31:02.000
And there was, it showed you giving a speech in Greenwood and you were talking about the Albany movement.

01:31:02.000 --> 01:31:12.000
Can you talk about what Greenwood was like then, what the Albany Georgia movement was like then, and sort of your role moving in and out of these communities?

01:31:12.000 --> 01:31:17.000
Well, you say it was a speech at Greenwood, I'm going to say rabble-roising.

01:31:17.000 --> 01:31:29.000
I was leading a singing, it was the only time that I've been able to sing with the Bobby Dylan Pete Seager.

01:31:29.000 --> 01:31:37.000
And, oh, I forget the name, just died.

01:31:38.000 --> 01:31:39.000
The folks sing it?

01:31:39.000 --> 01:31:43.000
Yeah, in theater of the cow, theater of the cow.

01:31:43.000 --> 01:31:52.000
But Greenwood and represents one of the triumphs in another way.

01:31:52.000 --> 01:32:06.000
Mrs. McGee who owned a farm was a militant person and who protected her farm with her sons and the use of firearms as a device.

01:32:07.000 --> 01:32:11.000
To keep off the clan and their sympathizers.

01:32:11.000 --> 01:32:26.000
Greenwood was a place where, again, local people who had no prior preparation for politics decided they had enough and they were going to participate in voter registration.

01:32:27.000 --> 01:32:40.000
And that little film, The Streets of Greenwood, is, I think it's only 20 minutes long, but it captures what was the essence of social change that affected people deeply.

01:32:41.000 --> 01:32:54.000
Where even people who couldn't pass the literacy test and therefore didn't even try to register the vote, felt obliged to help carry people in their cars to those places.

01:32:54.000 --> 01:33:02.000
People who couldn't pass the literacy test were defenders of those who did want to take the test.

01:33:02.000 --> 01:33:08.000
And it became a really a model of how people could stand up.

01:33:08.000 --> 01:33:25.000
Also, when they cut them off from the food stamps and so forth, Dick Gregory was helpful in getting money for food supplies to be shipped into Greenwood so those people could survive through the winter.

01:33:25.000 --> 01:33:30.000
So Greenwood represents a real place of triumph.

01:33:31.000 --> 01:33:42.000
The elected officials of Greenwood and the county are all majority black and as a result of the success of the Greenwood movement.

01:33:42.000 --> 01:33:53.000
Albany, Georgia as well, I referenced in doing one of my songs, we're not going to let Chief Pritchard turn us around.

01:33:53.000 --> 01:34:05.000
Chief Pritchard was one of the worst kind of redneck law enforcers or dislaw enforcers in Georgia.

01:34:05.000 --> 01:34:12.000
Albany, Georgia was a peculiar place because Southwest Georgia, all the attention was put in Atlanta and it was progressive.

01:34:13.000 --> 01:34:19.000
But Southwest Georgia had the heaviest population of black people in the state.

01:34:19.000 --> 01:34:30.000
And Southwest Georgia was neglected and Charles Shorod chose that as the place that he was going to spend his primary time.

01:34:31.000 --> 01:34:46.000
And Charles was also successful in mobilizing an organization that came around him in the grassroots fashion that was consistent with the Ella Baker's philosophy.

01:34:46.000 --> 01:35:00.000
They let the people decide what they wanted to do and the people of Albany came around and decided that they wanted to vote and they had marches and they had demonstrations and they went on for a night.

01:35:00.000 --> 01:35:06.000
Sometimes they were even surrounded by police in a hostile way.

01:35:07.000 --> 01:35:22.000
Police were not there to protect them, they were there to destroy them and in fact they had mobs that kept the blacks from who were assembled in those churches from even leaving for threat of violence.

01:35:23.000 --> 01:35:33.000
Albany represents the rankest, most ferocious expression of police sanctioned violence in the country.

01:35:33.000 --> 01:35:48.000
And maybe many people talk about the bull corner in Birmingham and others but there was never a police force that was more vicious and violent than Albany, Georgia.

01:35:48.000 --> 01:36:05.000
At a certain point they reached out and asked Dr. King to come and participate in some of the demonstrations and he to his great honor did get involved and get SCLC involved.

01:36:05.000 --> 01:36:19.000
And the revolution was really not so much what they did politically although they did change the politics in a sense that blacks were elected as well as able to vote ultimately.

01:36:19.000 --> 01:36:34.000
But Albany represents again one of those little spots of opportunity that Snick was able to open up as a demonstration to the entire South of what could be done once the people decide to do it.

01:36:35.000 --> 01:36:50.000
I know a lot of scholars and some SCLC voters have described Albany as a failure, the Albany movement as a failure. How would you respond to that?

01:36:50.000 --> 01:37:09.000
Well I think it depends on what perspective you came with in the first place. Was it the expectation that it was going to be a headline celebrity case, the vast movement of thousands of people that you had in Birmingham or in Montgomery.

01:37:09.000 --> 01:37:29.000
No Albany was a rural area off the side roads of history. There were no celebrated victories that came all of a sudden. It was gradual, it was slow, it was multi-year and there were no demonstrations that culminated in lots of television and so forth.

01:37:29.000 --> 01:37:45.000
There were handful of things that were covered by people like Sutton in the New York Times but others didn't cover it. It wasn't a focal point, it wasn't a flash point that led to something bigger and broader and more extraordinary.

01:37:45.000 --> 01:38:12.000
But it was, in my view, a tremendous success because people who were going to lose their homes suddenly were able to get the farmers' home support. They were able to understand how the intricacies of the public, the agriculture department had to be manipulated and understood to fill out the forms to get the different things.

01:38:12.000 --> 01:38:28.000
And even illustrated by the fact that Charles Charade's wife ultimately became the administrator for one of the Department of Agriculture's program in the Albany Georgia area.

01:38:28.000 --> 01:38:36.000
No, I don't think Albany was a fair year. It was just a slow boiling success instead of a rampant one.

01:38:36.000 --> 01:38:46.000
And that was Shirley Charade, it was in that major position. Was that the Department of Agriculture? Yes.

01:38:46.000 --> 01:38:56.000
Can you mention, you touched on it briefly, but can you tell us about that festival in Greenwood on Mrs. McGee's Farm? What was that like?

01:38:56.000 --> 01:39:18.000
Well, there was a peculiar confluence of people. It was intended to be a folk festival that would symbolize the culture of the region.

01:39:18.000 --> 01:39:36.000
All that people heard about the South made it sound like there was no culture there. But the Greenwood folk festival was to dispute that and to show that there was a great deal of culture that was not seen and not appreciated.

01:39:36.000 --> 01:39:48.000
And became a kind of institutional way in which the larger entertainment community could express its support for what the people of Greenwood were doing.

01:39:48.000 --> 01:40:05.000
And so they're coming together with names like Seagur and Dylan and Joan Baez and Bickel gave visibility to the people's struggle.

01:40:05.000 --> 01:40:17.000
In addition to the music and culture that those people represented. So that was the surrounding parameters of what the Greenwood folk festival was all about.

01:40:17.000 --> 01:40:32.000
You mentioned before that you did help to range concerts or performances for the freedom singers and that you spoke at events with the freedom singers. Can you talk about the freedom singers and their role?

01:40:32.000 --> 01:40:51.000
Well, you know, there was a history of the use of music for important purposes. There were the Jubilee singers of Fisk University. There were the Howard Gospel singers that operated for years and still operate.

01:40:51.000 --> 01:41:04.000
One of the things that Snick had as a component of its whole approach to these matters was the mobilization of the people through song.

01:41:04.000 --> 01:41:19.000
It was appreciated that particularly in the black community where music and religious vocalizing was an important part of the tradition of people.

01:41:19.000 --> 01:41:32.000
Incorporating those songs and taking some of the words of those songs and changing them to be more focused on the current movement was one of the things that Snick did.

01:41:32.000 --> 01:41:47.000
We shall overcome. It's really a song that Charles Tinley wrote. He was a minister in the Methodist church and he was in my hometown in Philadelphia.

01:41:47.000 --> 01:42:08.000
He made it as a religious ballot and of course with Jack Caravan and the Pete Seeger and the freedom singers we turned to say we shall overcome as a political anthem.

01:42:08.000 --> 01:42:25.000
But the whole business of the power of song is an important part of what the Snick was all about. It was one of the tools by which we could get the community investment and enthusiasm about what we wanted to do.

01:42:25.000 --> 01:42:39.000
And the songs had in addition to the spiritual content. They also had a reinforcing impact on the kids who were in demonstrations.

01:42:39.000 --> 01:42:51.000
So they could feel that there was solidarity and group involvement that gave them additional courage when they were locked up or when they even were in jail.

01:42:51.000 --> 01:42:58.000
They would sing those songs and be buoyed and encouraged to feel that they were not alone.

01:42:58.000 --> 01:43:05.000
And so all the words of those songs and all those songs that were part of the movement's hymn book.

01:43:05.000 --> 01:43:20.000
Each have peculiar meaning to people. And even now when you see the Snick people sing those songs, they all get misty eyed because those songs are so deeply connected to the history of the movement.

01:43:20.000 --> 01:43:33.000
You mentioned earlier that William Sloan Koffin helped raise money for you to go support Merleavers after my grubbers were assassinated.

01:43:33.000 --> 01:43:40.000
Yeah, I was of course a student at Law School in New Haven.

01:43:40.000 --> 01:43:51.000
And when we heard that the Metker had been assassinated we were stunned and had a loss for what to do.

01:43:51.000 --> 01:44:02.000
And Koffin had a long term association with the Women's League for Peace and Freedom.

01:44:02.000 --> 01:44:14.000
There is a great constitutional case called Up House versus Wyman on Freedom of Speech and Freedom of Assembly.

01:44:14.000 --> 01:44:21.000
And the Up House of that case is in Connecticut.

01:44:21.000 --> 01:44:37.000
And he was associated with leftist organizations all the time. And the Women's League for Peace and Freedom was one of those organizations that was on House on American Activities Committee's list and so forth.

01:44:37.000 --> 01:44:46.000
But they were still a vibrant organization and they considered that the Southern movement was part of their mission.

01:44:46.000 --> 01:45:06.000
And they raised money to enable me to both travel to Jackson and to actually be the first person out of the state to go to Merleavers' door with a check.

01:45:06.000 --> 01:45:16.000
From the Women's League for Peace and Freedom in Connecticut to let her know that she was not alone.

01:45:16.000 --> 01:45:26.000
What was that like to do that?

01:45:26.000 --> 01:45:40.000
I know that in the Memorial March in Jackson there was a confrontation between some of the marchers and the police.

01:45:40.000 --> 01:45:56.000
And I've heard it was a WBAI, is it the same? I've heard a recording of you and they denounced some of the people in that context. Do you tell them?

01:45:56.000 --> 01:46:11.000
Well, as you well know, you're talking about the aftermath of the funeral. Well, there's a public side and a private side.

01:46:11.000 --> 01:46:28.000
The public side was that, of course, there was this march after the funeral that was supposed to be a procession through a section of the city that had all been approved by the police and so forth.

01:46:28.000 --> 01:46:39.000
And the local youngsters and SNCC people didn't like the orderliness and the confinement of having a police escort and so forth.

01:46:39.000 --> 01:46:50.000
And they wanted to go in a different direction and sing freedom songs and not be as solemn as the main body of the funeral wanted to be.

01:46:50.000 --> 01:47:04.000
And so they broke off from the main march and we're going to go on another direction and of course the police made their response of trying to contain them and force them to go on the direction that they were chosen.

01:47:04.000 --> 01:47:17.000
And that led to the confrontation that I think is recorded on the, what's Judy Richardson's book or film series?

01:47:17.000 --> 01:47:24.000
Eyes on the prize. Eyes on the prize really describes that whole setting very thoroughly.

01:47:24.000 --> 01:47:35.000
The private side that was a role that I played that had never been exposed.

01:47:35.000 --> 01:47:53.000
And that was why I was at that demonstration. I was informed that there were a group of black veterans who were armed and were on the building surrounding the line of the march with an innocent man.

01:47:53.000 --> 01:48:07.000
And I was told that I'd better get up there or something was going to happen.

01:48:07.000 --> 01:48:22.000
And I went up to the roof overlooking the marchers just at the moment when John Doer, who was the assistant attorney general, put civil rights, stepped out in front of the crowd and eyes on the prize captures his statement down.

01:48:22.000 --> 01:48:32.000
John Doer, you know I stand for what was right. But from up on the roof they couldn't hear John Doer's words and they didn't know who John Doer was.

01:48:32.000 --> 01:48:42.000
And they thought that he was acting on behalf of the local police to contain and squelch the student protest.

01:48:42.000 --> 01:48:53.000
And they had telescopic rifles and they had John Doer lined up in their sights when I got to the roof.

01:48:53.000 --> 01:49:05.000
And I remember coming out there saying, stop in the name of Matthew. And they stopped.

01:49:05.000 --> 01:49:20.000
That, can you imagine what the history of civil rights would have been if black veterans had assassinated John Doer?

01:49:20.000 --> 01:49:25.000
No.

01:49:25.000 --> 01:49:30.000
I think I have a very different history.

01:49:30.000 --> 01:49:35.000
I've had what I consider three brushes with history.

01:49:35.000 --> 01:49:44.000
The first you mentioned was the business of having that first freedom school for the SNCC leaders.

01:49:45.000 --> 01:50:13.000
The second was in Atlanta when the SNCC affiliate called the Committee on Appeal for Human Rights was organizing a demonstration to go down to the, I guess, his hearts or the big department store in Atlanta.

01:50:13.000 --> 01:50:23.000
And there was a tremendous amount of pushback against that from the black leadership establishment.

01:50:23.000 --> 01:50:29.000
Their principle was that we don't have to have demonstrations in Atlanta.

01:50:29.000 --> 01:50:34.000
We're able to sit across the table and negotiate these things out.

01:50:34.000 --> 01:50:43.000
And so we don't, it's disruptive and unappropriate for Atlanta to have these demonstrations.

01:50:43.000 --> 01:50:52.000
And one of the promoters of that was Daddy King, Martin King's father, who was opposed to demonstrating in Atlanta.

01:50:52.000 --> 01:50:58.000
And we had this big meeting up, I guess it was in Morehouse's chapel.

01:50:58.000 --> 01:51:08.000
When the question was being hotly contested, whether we were going to have a demonstration, whether it was appropriate, whether we should follow the leadership of our elders, or whether we shouldn't.

01:51:08.000 --> 01:51:19.000
And I was one of the final speakers at that rally and urged that they go forward with the demonstration.

01:51:19.000 --> 01:51:31.000
And that they not only go forward with the demonstration, but that they take the root of the demonstration to Martin Luther King's house and ask him to come out and participate.

01:51:31.000 --> 01:51:40.000
In spite of the fact that his father was on the record as opposed to any such direct action in Atlanta.

01:51:40.000 --> 01:51:50.000
That was the decision of the group that they'd go forward with the demonstration and that they would call on Daddy King to join them.

01:51:50.000 --> 01:51:54.000
To his immortal credit, he did.

01:51:54.000 --> 01:52:09.000
When he participated in that demonstration, it resulted in his arrest just two days before the Kennedy Nixon election.

01:52:09.000 --> 01:52:28.000
And Bobby Kennedy sent Coretta King, a now famous telegram, saying that they would support in any way they could, Dr. King and his release and his protection in jail and so forth.

01:52:28.000 --> 01:52:57.000
That incident was then captured in leaflets and handouts by the United automobile workers and the United Packing House workers and distributed all across the major areas of the United States from Boston to Philadelphia to Newark to Chicago to Detroit to Houston.

01:52:57.000 --> 01:53:18.000
And it is statistically agreed that at the point of that date in the election cycle, the black world was equidistant between Kennedy and Nixon.

01:53:18.000 --> 01:53:39.000
After that torrent of leaflets and mobilization and communication in the black community, some 250,000 people who were not prepared to even vote did vote and they voted for Kennedy.

01:53:39.000 --> 01:53:46.000
Kennedy won that election by 100,000 votes.

01:53:46.000 --> 01:54:00.000
So I consider that that was the second place I had some contact with history and the third place was in the John Doar survival.

01:54:00.000 --> 01:54:10.000
That demonstration in Atlanta, was that in the Department of the Riches?

01:54:10.000 --> 01:54:21.000
Was that in conjunction with Smiths October of 1960 conference, the one that decided the organization to keep going and you had lined the mass meeting to close that?

01:54:21.000 --> 01:54:25.000
Is that the same? I know it was close in time, but I can't remember.

01:54:25.000 --> 01:54:33.000
So this was the unique thing that I'm recalling is the mass meeting for the demonstration.

01:54:33.000 --> 01:54:40.000
I don't remember any association that would a conference for say.

01:54:40.000 --> 01:54:43.000
The time in is close, but I'm not sure.

01:54:43.000 --> 01:54:51.000
It might have been connected, but I don't know. It's a strong connection in my mind.

01:54:51.000 --> 01:55:05.000
One of the things that I know that you remained involved with throughout this period of course is Smith's push in multiple directions for political power, voter registration and political power.

01:55:05.000 --> 01:55:15.000
And you mentioned not today, but in another context, a white lawyer from Mississippi Bill Higgs and the two of you worked on some things together?

01:55:15.000 --> 01:55:32.000
Well, in all fairness, I have to say that Bill was the guiding spirit in the business of that three judge court amendment being added to the Voting Rights Act.

01:55:33.000 --> 01:55:49.000
Bill Higgs, a beautiful guy, he was a native born, Mississippi, went to Old Smith and was also a Harvard Law graduate.

01:55:50.000 --> 01:56:06.000
And while he had many, many invitations and opportunities to merge with white upper crust of Mississippi, he chose to make his whole career in civil rights litigation.

01:56:06.000 --> 01:56:20.000
And he not only participated in helping to write that legislation, but in defending the other black lawyers who were frequently under attack in the courts, both federal as well as local.

01:56:20.000 --> 01:56:41.000
Judge Cox, who was a pointy resulting from Eastland being chairman of the Judiciary Committee, used to call blacks the N word in court and lawyers and submit them to all kinds of ignominities.

01:56:41.000 --> 01:56:59.000
And Bill Higgs was one of the few white lawyers in the South and probably the only white lawyer in Mississippi who would take civil rights cases fearlessly throughout his entire career.

01:56:59.000 --> 01:57:06.000
Did you ever know or hear of an attorney from Mississippi called named William Reedy Bill Reedy?

01:57:06.000 --> 01:57:07.000
I don't know.

01:57:07.000 --> 01:57:13.000
From Reedy, we just met him and I'm kind of placing.

01:57:13.000 --> 01:57:23.000
What were some of the things that you worked on in relation to voting and politics with SNCC that we haven't talked about?

01:57:23.000 --> 01:57:25.000
Will you involved with the NFDP?

01:57:25.000 --> 01:57:52.000
Oh yes. Larry Giyat, who was the president of the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party, gives me in the group of student lawyers that I was associated with during the summers that I was at Yale Law School.

01:57:52.000 --> 01:58:09.000
And I was with having found in the statutes of Mississippi the provision that allowed for protest voting and for the establishment of local political parties.

01:58:09.000 --> 01:58:23.000
That was the foundation for developing first mock elections for the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party and ultimately the participation in Democratic Party itself.

01:58:23.000 --> 01:58:35.000
That I think is, we found Bill Wood who was also a student at Yale Law School at the time working with me.

01:58:35.000 --> 01:58:52.000
And we found in the Mississippi Code a provision which really had been put there in the reconstruction era to protect white people who were then being excluded by the Republican Party that was controlling politics in Mississippi.

01:58:52.000 --> 01:59:00.000
And it allowed for protest votes and it allowed for challenges and it allowed for independent election activities.

01:59:00.000 --> 01:59:08.000
So that's one of the hooks and hooks of the Mississippi Law that we were able to find.

01:59:08.000 --> 01:59:27.000
Other work in the voter registration is most important in the years after SNCC where statewide mobilizations through the black elected officials, through the leadership conference of what is it called?

01:59:27.000 --> 01:59:49.000
I think it was called the Black Leadership Council or Forum that got behind the voter registration in a big way, getting the unions and getting others and creating this multiple foundations supported thing called the voter education project.

01:59:49.000 --> 02:00:03.000
The voter education project that was handed was headed for years by Leo Bryant and then by Vernon Jordan.

02:00:03.000 --> 02:00:14.000
It became a way in which philanthropic money could be channeled in a tax exempt way to voter registration.

02:00:14.000 --> 02:00:27.000
And crafting that and putting that together and making sure that it was adequately supported was one of the things that we were able to do in a unique way.

02:00:27.000 --> 02:00:40.000
And I think it made a lot of difference and I'm sure Vernon Jordan would be able to attest that much of the South and its change was largely the result of the voter education project.

02:00:40.000 --> 02:00:50.000
Significantly, however, the voter education project, VEP refused to go into Mississippi.

02:00:50.000 --> 02:01:07.000
And so when Bob Moses and SNCC went to McCormon to Greenwood, they were on their own because the voter education project considered that those places were too hot and too unlikely to have a result.

02:01:07.000 --> 02:01:19.000
So that made the heroic intervention of politics and visits to be all the more important.

02:01:19.000 --> 02:01:34.000
So that's very finely documented in an article by Dr. Larry Rivers that appeared in the journal African American History.

02:01:34.000 --> 02:01:50.000
And what it talks about is the influence that Mordekin Johnson had on the whole underpinnings philosophically of the direct action non-violence movement.

02:01:50.000 --> 02:02:08.000
That article called, I believe the Rankin Chapel and Howard University connection to Dr. Martin Luther King, something to add in fact.

02:02:08.000 --> 02:02:28.000
Mordekin Johnson was heard by Dr. King in Philadelphia at an occasion when Dr. Johnson was a student at Crozier Theological Seminary.

02:02:28.000 --> 02:02:43.000
And he'd come into Philadelphia for a weekend to hear this speaker Mordekin Wyatt Johnson.

02:02:43.000 --> 02:02:51.000
Mordekin Johnson was a mentor of mine as I mentioned when I was a student leader.

02:02:51.000 --> 02:03:03.000
But he was a person who also had spent a lifetime looking at the whole question of non-violence and international and national contact.

02:03:03.000 --> 02:03:18.000
And he was an officiagnato of Mahatma Gandhi. One of his vice presidents, William Stewart Nelson, even took a leave of absence from being vice president to go in and live in India.

02:03:18.000 --> 02:03:33.000
And he came back with such a vibrant impression of the power of non-violence that it became a cardinal part of what Mordekin spoke to the rest of his life.

02:03:34.000 --> 02:03:55.000
Dr. King was so impacted by that speech by Mordekin Johnson that he said he locked himself in his room for the next 10 days and read every book he could get on Mahatma Gandhi.

02:03:56.000 --> 02:04:03.000
And that was the change of his mind to see that non-violence was a cardinal part of his life.

02:04:04.000 --> 02:04:15.000
Frequently, it said that Dr. King's inspiration came from Thoreau and Emerson and Carlisle and Tillick.

02:04:16.000 --> 02:04:25.000
But if you listen to Mordekin, and if you listen to Dr. King himself, he attributed to Mordekin Johnson.

02:04:26.000 --> 02:04:35.000
I've heard him say that to me personally and he said it to history in a way that has been distorted by others and lost.

02:04:36.000 --> 02:04:44.000
Are there other things about the movement that we haven't talked about the mass movement of the 60s that you think are important?

02:04:45.000 --> 02:04:58.000
Well, I think that what we have to make sure is people don't think of a movement as something that only existed when there was a thing called SNCCR when the people were in the streets.

02:04:59.000 --> 02:05:10.000
There were successor organizations that adopted the techniques of SNCCR and direct action that have gone into the women's movement,

02:05:11.000 --> 02:05:21.000
that have gone into the movement for disabilities, that have gone into the movement of poor people, that have gone into the movement for income equality,

02:05:22.000 --> 02:05:29.000
that have gone into the movement for gender differentiation and protection.

02:05:30.000 --> 02:05:46.000
All of these things, in my view, benefit from the seeds of the direct movement of SNCCR and the techniques and the DNA of SNCCR is in all of those subsequent movements.

02:05:47.000 --> 02:06:01.000
The other thing that I would have on the record is that there are things that aren't related to direct action at all but are related to social change that were inspired by SNCCR.

02:06:02.000 --> 02:06:05.000
One of those is the National Conference of Black Lawyers.

02:06:06.000 --> 02:06:13.000
The National Conference of Black Lawyers was started in 1968 and on a call from Floyd McKissick,

02:06:14.000 --> 02:06:27.000
who thought that the black bar needed to move beyond just the narrow focus of civil rights as it was known up to Brown versus Board of Education,

02:06:28.000 --> 02:06:41.000
to get into other areas of federal regulations, federal and local economic development programs, poverty programs, housing programs,

02:06:41.000 --> 02:06:50.000
and other kinds of applications of defending the rights of the people who have no voice.

02:06:51.000 --> 02:07:00.000
And I think that there is a tendency to gain say the relevance of those earlier movements on those later movements.

02:07:00.000 --> 02:07:16.000
When you look at those lawyers who made up the National Conference of Black Lawyers, or started in 1968, they just had their 100 and I'm not 100,

02:07:17.000 --> 02:07:24.000
their 46th anniversary conference in Durham, North Carolina this summer.

02:07:25.000 --> 02:07:43.000
The people who went through that, Judge Leon Higginboff from the Third Circuit, Nathan Jones, Chief Judge of the Ninth Circuit, Bruce Wright, the New York Court.

02:07:44.000 --> 02:08:00.000
Any number of judges, any number of lawyers, Raymond P. S. Alexander, who handled the case of the Droid College case that established that there could be no discrimination in charitable funded organizations,

02:08:01.000 --> 02:08:10.000
that was all the offspring of the direct action campaign that went in other directions.

02:08:11.000 --> 02:08:19.000
And I think it's significant to know that institutions like the National Conference of Black Lawyers have been felt in other ways.

02:08:20.000 --> 02:08:26.000
They defeated the appointment of Haines' work in calls well to the Supreme Court of the United States.

02:08:27.000 --> 02:08:40.000
They have been working the hand of SNCC is under a lot of things moving in an invisible way to change society and America.

02:08:41.000 --> 02:08:47.000
And it's not known except for those few of us who have been part of both that they're really the same movement.

02:08:48.000 --> 02:08:57.000
So speaking of that, historically and today are very strong SNCC presence in Washington DC.

02:08:58.000 --> 02:09:06.000
Is there an explanation for how many SNCC people came to be in Washington and something of what they've done in the United States?

02:09:07.000 --> 02:09:15.000
Well, of course the big magnet is Mary and Barry, this so-called mayor for life.

02:09:16.000 --> 02:09:34.000
Mary and Barry interestingly enough wrote me a four-page letter when he was still a student in which he outlined the importance of blacks taking over the political structures in the localities wherever they lived.

02:09:34.000 --> 02:09:46.000
Mary and also made sure that while he was mayor, every level of hierarchy was integrated.

02:09:47.000 --> 02:09:53.000
He also made sure that women were given responsibilities that previously were never considered for women.

02:09:54.000 --> 02:10:14.000
He made sure that the programs that the city supported went in areas that never before had been funded like summer jobs programs and playground improvements and dealing with problems for the elderly and housing for the homeless.

02:10:15.000 --> 02:10:23.000
Mary and Barry is an illustration of how pervasive this thing has been.

02:10:24.000 --> 02:10:32.000
But you can really trace in other directions you can go to Harold Washington in Chicago and see his impact.

02:10:32.000 --> 02:10:41.000
You can look at some of the lawyers who were in San Francisco who had their experience dealing with the Panthers.

02:10:42.000 --> 02:10:53.000
You can look at the representation of the prisoners in Attica prison and the solar dad brothers and the Bobby Seal case.

02:10:54.000 --> 02:11:18.000
The law has benefited tremendously because of this foundational kind of leavening that the direct action campaign required as a shake-up in the concept of what law should be and the due process should be and what representation of people who don't have funds.

02:11:18.000 --> 02:11:27.000
And really a leveling field that takes the economics out of the business of enjoying human rights.

02:11:28.000 --> 02:11:39.000
What are some of the ways that participation in the movement has shaped you and your career life and your work and your values?

02:11:40.000 --> 02:11:46.000
Well, if you look at my resume, you see that I've done a number of things.

02:11:47.000 --> 02:11:59.000
But I have to say that all of them have been related to the kind of experience and orientation that I had the benefit of being exposed to in SNCC and in the student campaign.

02:12:00.000 --> 02:12:04.000
I was co-chairman in National Conference of Black Wires at one point.

02:12:05.000 --> 02:12:16.000
I was a member of the governing board for the Postal Service in Chairman of the Corporate Responsibility Committee.

02:12:16.000 --> 02:12:20.000
I appointed by President Carter and confirmed by the Senate.

02:12:21.000 --> 02:12:33.000
But I was able, while there, to create a focus on the discrimination against blacks that had been hidden for a long time.

02:12:34.000 --> 02:12:44.000
Woodrow Wilson started it when he relegated blacks who had been successful in the Postal Service to menial jobs.

02:12:44.000 --> 02:12:46.000
He did that across throughout the federal government.

02:12:46.000 --> 02:12:50.000
But in the Postal Service, we were able to reverse that.

02:12:50.000 --> 02:13:03.000
And as chair of the Corporate Responsibility Committee, I was able to get Dr. Kenneth Clark of Brown vs. Board of Education fame to come in and study the Postal Service and see that all the systemic

02:13:03.000 --> 02:13:10.000
manifestations of discrimination that need to be overturned and the regulations were modified.

02:13:10.000 --> 02:13:26.000
I was even able, sitting in that position, to do something about the discrimination that had impacted Zamzi Moore, one of our earlier participants in the Mississippi voter registration, to get his pension restored.

02:13:27.000 --> 02:13:32.000
I've had international expansions of this.

02:13:32.000 --> 02:13:52.000
I was a consultant to the High Commissioner on Human Rights in Geneva to look at the whole way in which the information highway is passing by poor and ineffluent and sometimes racially segregated communities.

02:13:53.000 --> 02:13:59.000
This, I think, is something that has continued in my career.

02:13:59.000 --> 02:14:09.000
I was in education in different ways as a professor at both Howard University's Law School and the David A. Clark School Law.

02:14:09.000 --> 02:14:16.000
But I was also in the Board of Trustees at both of those institutions, Howard and University of District of Columbia.

02:14:16.000 --> 02:14:21.000
And I served as president of the University of District of Columbia.

02:14:22.000 --> 02:14:28.000
All those things have been part of the whole civil rights orientation.

02:14:28.000 --> 02:14:42.000
Even my business activity and dealing with export import, the exports and imports that I was engaged in was from Africa and the Middle East that didn't have access to the United States.

02:14:42.000 --> 02:14:48.000
I was sensitized to that exclusion during my era of civil rights.

02:14:48.000 --> 02:15:02.000
There are other aspects of dealing with the, the, the, justifying the rights of publishers to be heard and publishing houses to be funded in ways that bypass the big houses that exclude.

02:15:02.000 --> 02:15:21.000
I helped put together the broadcast station, W-H-U-T, which is the only full commercial station that is owned by a historically black college in university.

02:15:21.000 --> 02:15:29.000
And they also have a allied commercial FM station.

02:15:29.000 --> 02:15:39.000
What I'm able to say is that for me the movement didn't stop and just changed forms.

02:15:39.000 --> 02:15:47.000
So whereas one time you were on the street, now you're in the sweets, but you're carrying out the same mission.

02:15:47.000 --> 02:15:57.000
I wrote a letter in the twilight of SNCC to John Lewis, who was in chairman.

02:15:57.000 --> 02:16:16.000
Saying that I thought SNCC people ought to make it their business to professionally infiltrate the machinery that was being created by the legislation that we drafted.

02:16:16.000 --> 02:16:37.000
I thought that SNCC people should migrate into the organizations like the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, like the National Labor Relations Board, like the Federal Reserve.

02:16:37.000 --> 02:16:51.000
But all these different things that are subsequent to the movement are still relevant to the movement, but they're being administered by people who are indifferent to the movement.

02:16:51.000 --> 02:17:01.000
It was my observation that labor after passing legislation then put their people forward to be the people who administer it.

02:17:01.000 --> 02:17:15.000
We did not do that. And I urge, I think that that's one of the shortcomings of our movement that needs to be corrected in the notion that you're selling out because you're going into the belly of the beast.

02:17:15.000 --> 02:17:29.000
But you're going in with a different mission than just during a paycheck. And that's what needs to be highlighted as a career goal for people with sensitive and concerned.

02:17:29.000 --> 02:17:58.000
I think it's also one of the shortcomings of the movement that we went through the era of black power, that we lost connection with the more progressive elements of the white community and did not have the foresight to continue the alliances that are so critical for real social change.

02:17:58.000 --> 02:18:23.000
It's my view that the reason we have now a red-state, blue-state kind of situation in such categorical terms throughout the South is because we did not fulfill the mission of mobilizing the poor white community to what their real interests are.

02:18:23.000 --> 02:18:43.000
And so you have people in the state of Kentucky voting to kill health care provisions that are aimed to alleviate the kind of conditions they're suffering under because they don't want to be associated with Obama and an Obama care.

02:18:43.000 --> 02:18:57.000
If we had been able to do in the poor white community what we were able to do in the poor black community we would have a different politics today.

02:18:57.000 --> 02:19:18.000
And I think the challenge that's left for the next generation is to undo that era. Part of it was brought about by the egotism of some of those involved with black power that wanted to exclude whites but also by the myopia of seeing that the problem is really broader than race.

02:19:18.000 --> 02:19:41.000
It deals with the human rights question, not the civil rights question and it requires that the poor people who are affected by the same oppressive legislative provisions, the same migration of income from the bottom to the top are not racially divided.

02:19:41.000 --> 02:20:00.000
And that's the part of the unfulfilled mission that the next snake is to fulfill. We were not the first snake. There was a Southern Negro Youth Congress that was a progressive organization of the 40s. That was the first snake.

02:20:00.000 --> 02:20:16.000
And that was molded around the kinds of thoughts that WB Du Bois had and some of the thoughts that the Eleanor Roosevelt had about the need for youth to be involved with the questions of poverty.

02:20:16.000 --> 02:20:24.000
Hopefully there'll be another snake after this that will fulfill what was the promise that we missed.

02:20:24.000 --> 02:20:28.000
Thank you very much for the good place to end.

02:20:28.000 --> 02:20:30.000
Cool.

02:20:30.000 --> 02:20:40.000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

